WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:21.120
This is the first in a two-part series of webinars I'm going to present on extracting

00:00:21.120 --> 00:00:22.760
data from the web.

00:00:22.760 --> 00:00:26.520
And what we're going to look at today is how to get data that's been already packaged for

00:00:26.520 --> 00:00:28.200
you in a web API.

00:00:28.200 --> 00:00:30.840
A lot of times when people want to share their data through the web, they go through the

00:00:30.840 --> 00:00:34.759
trouble to make an API, which makes it easier for you to get that data.

00:00:34.759 --> 00:00:40.119
On November 30th, we'll follow up this with a web scraping webinar, which will show you

00:00:40.119 --> 00:00:44.279
how to just go out and scrape the data that you want right off the web pages when it's

00:00:44.279 --> 00:00:47.439
not been prepackaged into an API.

00:00:47.439 --> 00:00:51.400
The topic that we're going to cover today touches on something very deep, and that is

00:00:51.400 --> 00:00:55.480
actually the topic of web APIs and web development.

00:00:55.480 --> 00:00:59.599
And I'm not going to go so deep into that.

00:00:59.599 --> 00:01:01.720
That's not my expertise.

00:01:01.720 --> 00:01:07.360
And what I will be teaching you is a package called HTTR, which is an R package that allows

00:01:07.360 --> 00:01:15.320
you to use HTTP web APIs with R. The HTTR package is actually very simple to use.

00:01:15.320 --> 00:01:21.080
So if you are a web developer and you are familiar with HTTP, I suggest that maybe you

00:01:21.080 --> 00:01:23.639
just look at the vignette, the quick start vignette for HTTR.

00:01:23.639 --> 00:01:27.480
It's about 1,500 words, probably take you less than 10 minutes to read, which is shorter

00:01:27.480 --> 00:01:28.480
than this webinar.

00:01:28.480 --> 00:01:32.239
And I put the link up here right now in case you're watching this in the future right now

00:01:32.239 --> 00:01:34.959
and you think this might be a better way for you to ramp up.

00:01:34.959 --> 00:01:40.120
Because what I'm going to do is focus on what HTTP is, what web APIs are.

00:01:40.120 --> 00:01:45.559
And I'm going to assume that the people who need this webinar are people who have a background

00:01:45.559 --> 00:01:50.639
like me, where you're a data scientist or statistician, you've identified the web as

00:01:50.639 --> 00:01:55.919
a great place to collect data, but you don't have that background in APIs or web development.

00:01:55.919 --> 00:01:59.599
So you don't necessarily have the context to use the HTTR package, which like I said

00:01:59.599 --> 00:02:03.440
is a fairly easy package, as you'll see when we get to that.

00:02:03.440 --> 00:02:07.199
So before we start explaining what web APIs are and whatnot, I do want to acknowledge

00:02:07.199 --> 00:02:13.039
that these two webinars both come from a tutorial that I taught with Scott Chamberlain and Karthik

00:02:13.039 --> 00:02:15.800
Graham at the last UseR! conference.

00:02:15.800 --> 00:02:19.279
Now the webinars are more concise and self-contained, there's no exercises for you to do.

00:02:19.279 --> 00:02:25.440
So the contents of these webinars we will put on the RStudio webinar GitHub, like we

00:02:25.440 --> 00:02:26.440
always do.

00:02:26.440 --> 00:02:30.919
But if you wanted access to the original content, it is available through the ROpenSci GitHub

00:02:30.919 --> 00:02:33.399
repository, which is the link right here.

00:02:33.399 --> 00:02:37.559
So that's the original tutorial at UseR!, which is much longer and has exercises and

00:02:37.559 --> 00:02:38.559
whatnot.

00:02:38.559 --> 00:02:43.720
All right, so let's start with APIs.

00:02:43.720 --> 00:02:45.960
What is an API in general?

00:02:46.039 --> 00:02:50.679
You can think of an API as a set of instructions for how a program should interact with a piece

00:02:50.679 --> 00:02:52.179
of software.

00:02:52.179 --> 00:02:56.160
So if you create a piece of software that does something useful and you think someone

00:02:56.160 --> 00:02:59.960
who's writing a program somewhere else might want to use your software, you would set up

00:02:59.960 --> 00:03:05.520
an API which tells that developer how their program should send requests or interact with

00:03:05.520 --> 00:03:07.479
your piece of software.

00:03:07.479 --> 00:03:13.360
And an API can be an interface to a database, to a computer's operating system, to a software

00:03:13.360 --> 00:03:18.399
package that does something, or commonly to web applications.

00:03:18.399 --> 00:03:20.039
And we're going to focus on this last case today.

00:03:20.039 --> 00:03:26.119
We're going to focus on how you can use an API to a web data source to collect data into

00:03:26.119 --> 00:03:27.119
R.

00:03:27.119 --> 00:03:34.919
And if you wanted to visualize, you know, how APIs work, you could imagine or you could

00:03:34.919 --> 00:03:38.479
think of something that you do every day that involves an API in the background, and that's

00:03:38.479 --> 00:03:40.360
browsing the Internet.

00:03:40.360 --> 00:03:45.440
When you open a web page on your computer, the pictures that you see on the web page,

00:03:45.440 --> 00:03:51.320
the text, the links, all that exists somewhere on a server on the other side of the Internet.

00:03:51.320 --> 00:03:56.839
And your web browser on your computer locates that server that's storing all this information.

00:03:56.839 --> 00:04:02.000
It sends a request to the server using the server's web API, saying, please give me the

00:04:02.000 --> 00:04:06.759
pictures so I can display them on my user's screen, and here she could see what's on your

00:04:06.759 --> 00:04:07.759
web page.

00:04:07.759 --> 00:04:11.160
And then the server sends a response back that hopefully contains the pictures and the

00:04:11.160 --> 00:04:14.320
text, everything the web browser needs to build that web page locally for you to look

00:04:14.320 --> 00:04:15.479
at.

00:04:15.479 --> 00:04:18.839
Or the server might send back some sort of error message saying, I can't do that for

00:04:18.839 --> 00:04:19.839
whatever reason.

00:04:19.839 --> 00:04:25.720
The instructions, the requests that your web browser sends to the server, are formatted

00:04:25.720 --> 00:04:30.440
according to the API that that server uses, or that that program uses.

00:04:30.440 --> 00:04:39.799
So when you write a piece of software, like I guess Tim Berners-Lee wrote the Internet,

00:04:39.799 --> 00:04:41.720
you can decide how you want this all to work.

00:04:41.720 --> 00:04:44.640
And then anyone who wants to work with that software should follow your rules, otherwise

00:04:44.640 --> 00:04:46.519
your software's not going to respond the way that they want.

00:04:46.519 --> 00:04:50.679
So when your web browser connects to a web server, there's a specific way of doing that

00:04:50.679 --> 00:04:55.839
that your web browser uses, and that is with an API protocol called HTTP.

00:04:55.839 --> 00:04:59.200
And that's what we're going to look at here today.

00:04:59.200 --> 00:05:04.320
So HTTP is standard for all sorts of web interfaces.

00:05:04.320 --> 00:05:06.959
I mentioned before my background's not in web development.

00:05:06.959 --> 00:05:11.359
I imagine there are some exotic places where you might find something other than HTTP,

00:05:11.359 --> 00:05:13.799
experimental locations, but really I don't know of any.

00:05:13.799 --> 00:05:16.760
So I think HTTP is pretty standard.

00:05:16.760 --> 00:05:21.600
What we're going to try to do today is use the HTR package to equip R to behave like

00:05:21.600 --> 00:05:27.559
a web browser, in that it can fetch resources from a web server straight into R.

00:05:27.720 --> 00:05:31.119
Those resources could be things you see on a web page like images and text, or they could

00:05:31.119 --> 00:05:37.160
be actual data that's been saved on the Internet for you to download.

00:05:37.160 --> 00:05:42.600
So let's look at HTTP, the protocol that we'll use in our web APIs.

00:05:42.600 --> 00:05:45.079
It stands for Hypertext Transfer Protocol.

00:05:45.079 --> 00:05:48.440
The Internet is basically built on hypertext, which is text that's linked to other pieces

00:05:48.440 --> 00:05:50.279
of text and so on.

00:05:50.279 --> 00:05:56.559
And HTTP itself revolves around the idea of URLs, which is another acronym for Uniform

00:05:57.000 --> 00:05:58.000
Resource Locator.

00:05:58.000 --> 00:06:03.720
And a URL is what you know as a web address, it's what you type into your web browsers.

00:06:03.720 --> 00:06:10.720
And you can think of a URL more generally as a file path to a resource on the Internet.

00:06:11.320 --> 00:06:17.279
Just like a file path on your computer, there are different parts to this URL that directs

00:06:17.279 --> 00:06:20.519
your computer to the actual resource, the server to the actual resource.

00:06:20.519 --> 00:06:24.519
This is how you identify the resources that you want to request or that you want to alter

00:06:24.600 --> 00:06:28.600
or delete or whatever you want to do through the API.

00:06:28.600 --> 00:06:35.600
And just going back to this, there are different parts of this URL that I've put here, and

00:06:37.279 --> 00:06:39.920
many of them are optional.

00:06:39.920 --> 00:06:44.799
You very often won't have query parameters or an ID or whatnot, but all these things

00:06:44.799 --> 00:06:47.040
can work together to form a URL.

00:06:47.040 --> 00:06:52.040
Or you might be able to get resources as simple as www.host.com.

00:06:52.600 --> 00:06:59.600
The way HTTP is organized is you make requests, the client makes requests that are sent to

00:07:01.920 --> 00:07:05.279
the server, and then the server responds with responses.

00:07:05.279 --> 00:07:11.279
And both the request message and the response message are basically plain text files, and

00:07:11.279 --> 00:07:13.320
they share the same structure.

00:07:13.320 --> 00:07:18.519
So plain text is really easy to pass over the Internet or over any network.

00:07:18.519 --> 00:07:21.119
And so HTTP is taking advantage of that.

00:07:21.160 --> 00:07:27.079
If you wanted to look at an HTTP message that is sent, whether it's a response or a request,

00:07:27.079 --> 00:07:28.839
it's going to have the same three-part structure.

00:07:28.839 --> 00:07:32.200
There's going to be an initial line that contains very important information.

00:07:32.200 --> 00:07:36.399
What's in that line will depend on whether or not this is a request or a response.

00:07:36.399 --> 00:07:39.519
We'll look at those separately in a moment.

00:07:39.519 --> 00:07:44.040
There's going to be, or there can be, a set of optional headers, which are just key value

00:07:44.040 --> 00:07:46.359
pairs separated by a colon.

00:07:46.359 --> 00:07:48.359
Those can contain useful information.

00:07:48.480 --> 00:07:52.880
And then also optionally, there may be a message body at the end of the message, separated

00:07:52.880 --> 00:07:55.480
from the beginning by a blank line.

00:07:55.480 --> 00:08:00.640
And that message body is where contents would be if the message contains an image or a data

00:08:00.640 --> 00:08:01.640
set or whatnot.

00:08:01.640 --> 00:08:05.920
It would be stored here in the message body.

00:08:05.920 --> 00:08:09.640
If it helps, and it helps me, I like to think of these three parts as separate from each

00:08:09.640 --> 00:08:15.000
other, and this is how we divide up this template message.

00:08:15.000 --> 00:08:17.000
So let's look at a sample request.

00:08:17.000 --> 00:08:21.200
You can't get a response from a server until you send a request, so you need to learn how

00:08:21.200 --> 00:08:24.519
to send a request before you learn how to interpret a response.

00:08:24.519 --> 00:08:32.679
And this would be a real HTTP request going out to the webinars page of RStudio.com, which

00:08:32.679 --> 00:08:37.239
is somewhere you've probably visited if you managed to wind up here, and it's just asking

00:08:37.239 --> 00:08:42.280
for the information that a web browser would need to display this webpage on your computer.

00:08:42.280 --> 00:08:46.960
If we look at it, we can see it has that three-part structure, although since this request is

00:08:46.960 --> 00:08:51.039
not really sending information for the server to use, it's just saying, please server, give

00:08:51.039 --> 00:08:52.039
me something back.

00:08:52.039 --> 00:08:53.039
There's no body.

00:08:53.039 --> 00:08:54.039
There's no content to it.

00:08:54.039 --> 00:09:00.359
It's just an initial line and some headers with some metadata.

00:09:00.359 --> 00:09:04.200
And this initial line is broken into three parts, and this is how the initial line of

00:09:04.200 --> 00:09:08.159
any HTTP request will be organized.

00:09:08.159 --> 00:09:12.760
The first line will be broken into three parts, each separated by a space, and the last part

00:09:12.760 --> 00:09:14.200
for a request is the most trivial.

00:09:14.200 --> 00:09:17.919
It's the version of HTTP that the request is using.

00:09:17.919 --> 00:09:22.679
We're not going to have to pay attention to that today.

00:09:22.679 --> 00:09:28.559
Next part is the URL path to the resource that the message is pertaining to, and you'll

00:09:28.559 --> 00:09:33.359
notice that this isn't a complete URL path, but your computer will have already established

00:09:33.359 --> 00:09:38.359
a connection through a port to the host, which is www.rstudio.com, so the host knows what

00:09:38.359 --> 00:09:39.359
it is.

00:09:39.359 --> 00:09:42.440
The host needs to know where in all of its files is the resource you want to know about,

00:09:42.440 --> 00:09:44.479
and that's the remaining part of the URL.

00:09:44.479 --> 00:09:50.599
So here, resources slash webinars takes you to the webinars page of rstudio.com.

00:09:50.599 --> 00:09:54.919
And then the first part of the first line is probably the most important part of your

00:09:54.919 --> 00:10:01.119
request, and that is an HTTP verb that tells the server what you want to do.

00:10:01.119 --> 00:10:07.280
There are a collection, a small collection of verbs that you can use with HTTP, but the

00:10:07.280 --> 00:10:10.359
most important ones are probably the four that I'm going to list here.

00:10:10.359 --> 00:10:15.599
We're using a get verb in that sample, and get is the verb you use when you want to retrieve

00:10:15.599 --> 00:10:17.640
a resource that's specified by a URL.

00:10:17.640 --> 00:10:21.159
You send a get request to the server, and the server knows that it should send you back

00:10:21.159 --> 00:10:26.039
what you're asking for, or tell you that you can't have it, it doesn't exist, you know,

00:10:26.039 --> 00:10:27.039
something like that.

00:10:27.039 --> 00:10:34.119
You can also send a post request, which creates the resource out of URL.

00:10:34.119 --> 00:10:38.200
So when you send a post request to a server, you normally attach some data to it, the server

00:10:38.200 --> 00:10:42.559
gets this, and then it uses that data to build a new resource at that URL, which will then

00:10:42.559 --> 00:10:46.320
exist and other people can get it and use it.

00:10:46.320 --> 00:10:50.520
You can use a put request, which is similar to post, but it works with resources that

00:10:50.520 --> 00:10:51.520
already exist.

00:10:51.520 --> 00:10:55.200
You use a put to update that resource with data that you store in the contents of your

00:10:55.200 --> 00:10:56.479
message.

00:10:56.479 --> 00:10:59.919
And then you can also send a delete request, which would delete a resource that exists

00:10:59.919 --> 00:11:02.760
on that server at that URL.

00:11:02.760 --> 00:11:06.000
So like I said, there's other verbs, but these are the big four, the most important

00:11:06.000 --> 00:11:07.000
ones.

00:11:07.000 --> 00:11:11.000
And this is really the place where you as an R developer need to start paying attention.

00:11:11.000 --> 00:11:16.239
So the information up to here was all contextual, it's all about how the web is created, but

00:11:16.239 --> 00:11:21.119
these verbs are things that you will use from inside of R.

00:11:21.119 --> 00:11:22.599
So let's start doing that.

00:11:22.599 --> 00:11:28.440
The package that will use an R to send HTTP requests and receive responses is called hitter.

00:11:28.440 --> 00:11:32.679
It's like HTTP, but it ends with an R.

00:11:32.679 --> 00:11:36.919
To use it, you can install it from CRAN like any package and then load it with library.

00:11:36.919 --> 00:11:41.400
And to create a request with hitter, you would use a function that matches one of the verb

00:11:41.400 --> 00:11:42.400
names.

00:11:42.400 --> 00:11:45.880
Notice these names are all capitalized, so if you wanted to send a get request, you would

00:11:45.880 --> 00:11:52.200
use the get function, which comes in hitter, and it's capital G-E-T.

00:11:52.200 --> 00:11:57.840
What you pass to get is the complete URL of the resource you want to get.

00:11:57.840 --> 00:12:01.159
There's also a function, for example, called post, and then you pass a complete URL where

00:12:01.159 --> 00:12:06.200
you want to post the new data to, and so on.

00:12:06.200 --> 00:12:12.559
We saw in our HTTP file that the actual HTTP request sort of divides up this URL, but you

00:12:12.559 --> 00:12:14.640
as an R user don't have to worry about that.

00:12:14.640 --> 00:12:18.440
Get is an R function, and it's going to do some preprocessing in the background for you.

00:12:18.440 --> 00:12:22.400
All get needs is the complete URL, and it'll take care of the rest there.

00:12:22.400 --> 00:12:26.119
And then notice I'm saving something from this function.

00:12:26.119 --> 00:12:29.919
Once get sends the request, in this case over the internet, so you don't want to be connected

00:12:29.919 --> 00:12:35.440
to the internet, but the server it accesses is going to send back a response, and get

00:12:35.440 --> 00:12:38.320
will return that response as the output of the function.

00:12:38.320 --> 00:12:40.799
So if I want to use that response later, I'm going to save it, and here I'm going to save

00:12:40.799 --> 00:12:43.880
it to the object R.

00:12:43.880 --> 00:12:49.520
I'm accessing here a website called httpbin.org, and that's on purpose.

00:12:49.520 --> 00:12:55.679
This is a website that was set up as a learning age for HTTP, and basically when you access

00:12:55.679 --> 00:12:58.919
something there, it just sends back the thing that you sent to it.

00:12:58.919 --> 00:13:05.320
So if I'm sending a get message to httpbin.org.get, httpbin is going to take that message, quickly

00:13:05.320 --> 00:13:08.719
recompile it into a response, and send it back to me so I can kind of see what's going

00:13:08.719 --> 00:13:09.719
on behind the scenes.

00:13:09.719 --> 00:13:13.159
I can see what I sent.

00:13:13.159 --> 00:13:18.080
If you want to add headers into the HTTP message request that you're sending over, you could

00:13:18.080 --> 00:13:23.500
do that by adding the add headers function as an argument, an unnamed argument, inside

00:13:23.500 --> 00:13:24.599
of your verb function.

00:13:24.599 --> 00:13:29.719
So here I'm adding it inside the get function.

00:13:29.719 --> 00:13:33.840
Pass to add headers a set of named arguments that you want to become your headers.

00:13:33.840 --> 00:13:37.000
So I'm just making up a stupid header that no server would know what to do with, but

00:13:37.000 --> 00:13:43.520
I'm saying add this header, name equals Garrett, that's my name, and what get and add headers

00:13:43.520 --> 00:13:44.520
will do in the background.

00:13:44.520 --> 00:13:47.320
So when it assembles your message, your message will look like this.

00:13:47.320 --> 00:13:51.039
Here's the first line we see, our get, that's the verb.

00:13:51.039 --> 00:13:56.840
The part of the URL that is needed to go from the host to the resource, which is just

00:13:56.840 --> 00:14:01.159
slash get, and then the protocol we're using, which is HTTP 1.1.

00:14:01.159 --> 00:14:07.440
And then there's a header, and it's the header I added, name colon get.

00:14:07.440 --> 00:14:12.840
The name of the argument that you select will be the key value of that key value pair, and

00:14:12.840 --> 00:14:16.679
then what you set that name to will be the value of the key value pair.

00:14:17.320 --> 00:14:22.119
Well, the third part of any HTTP message is a body, and if you want to add a body to your

00:14:22.119 --> 00:14:25.520
message, you could do that with the body argument.

00:14:25.520 --> 00:14:29.280
So normally when you send a get message, you don't need to add a body.

00:14:29.280 --> 00:14:32.919
You're asking the server to send you data, so you sending data to the server is kind

00:14:32.919 --> 00:14:37.080
of unnecessary, and it wouldn't be used if it arrived.

00:14:37.080 --> 00:14:41.760
So I'm going to use the post verb here, so the post function creates a post request,

00:14:41.760 --> 00:14:45.799
and post is the verb that you use to create a new resource on the server.

00:14:45.799 --> 00:14:49.159
That new resource that you want to create, you need to pass to the server in the body

00:14:49.159 --> 00:14:53.679
of your function, of your request.

00:14:53.679 --> 00:14:58.400
So here I've saved a list with three elements named A, B, and C, two body.

00:14:58.400 --> 00:15:02.119
I saved my URL separately, but I'm passing it into post.

00:15:02.119 --> 00:15:03.119
There's my URL.

00:15:03.119 --> 00:15:07.760
Then I'm sending the body argument equal to this list that I created, and saying I want

00:15:07.760 --> 00:15:11.119
this resource to exist on the server, and I want people to be able to access it through

00:15:11.119 --> 00:15:13.520
that URL that I just made.

00:15:13.520 --> 00:15:18.039
And then you could choose how to encode that data that you're sending along.

00:15:18.039 --> 00:15:21.119
So if you're working in R, the data that you put together is probably going to be a list,

00:15:21.119 --> 00:15:25.719
which is an R object that a web API won't know what to do with.

00:15:25.719 --> 00:15:30.599
So the header is going to transform that data into something that's more commonly used by

00:15:30.599 --> 00:15:35.039
web APIs, and you can choose with the encode argument how you want to do that.

00:15:35.039 --> 00:15:39.000
To learn more about encodes, look at that whole page for post, but basically you can

00:15:39.000 --> 00:15:44.200
encode as a form, as multi-type data, as raw data, which would just be binary data,

00:15:44.200 --> 00:15:45.200
or as JSON.

00:15:45.200 --> 00:15:51.400
And here, let's make a, well, let's review these arguments, and then I want to make a

00:15:51.400 --> 00:15:54.320
small tangent to explain what JSON is.

00:15:54.320 --> 00:15:55.760
So here's our body argument.

00:15:55.760 --> 00:15:57.400
That's the data we're going to send across.

00:15:57.400 --> 00:16:00.840
Here's how I want to encode it, and this last line I'm going to encode as JSON, but you

00:16:00.840 --> 00:16:03.840
can see in the other lines how to do it differently.

00:16:03.840 --> 00:16:05.679
And then this is what I would get.

00:16:05.679 --> 00:16:07.719
This is the message that would be sent to the server.

00:16:07.719 --> 00:16:10.080
Now the verb is post.

00:16:10.080 --> 00:16:12.960
The remaining path in the URL is slash post.

00:16:12.960 --> 00:16:15.400
You see our protocol there.

00:16:15.400 --> 00:16:20.159
Post itself has created a fairly informative header that we didn't have to worry about.

00:16:20.159 --> 00:16:25.719
And then the body, the very last line of this request, contains our very simple list, A

00:16:25.719 --> 00:16:29.679
equals one, B equals two, C equals three, but it's been encoded as JSON, which is something

00:16:29.679 --> 00:16:32.599
that almost anything on the web will know what to do with.

00:16:32.599 --> 00:16:35.200
So let's look at what JSON is.

00:16:35.679 --> 00:16:38.159
So you'll be familiar with it.

00:16:38.159 --> 00:16:39.159
It's another acronym.

00:16:39.159 --> 00:16:46.000
It stands for JavaScript Object Notation, and it is also a type of key value pairs organized

00:16:46.000 --> 00:16:49.520
hierarchically into a group.

00:16:49.520 --> 00:16:52.119
It's becoming the standard data format for web APIs.

00:16:52.119 --> 00:16:56.520
There are other formats out there like XML and so on, but you will probably see JSON,

00:16:56.520 --> 00:17:00.799
and as you start working with web data and go a little further, you will encounter it.

00:17:00.799 --> 00:17:05.040
But I wanted you to just be aware of what's there in terms of JSON, and also a tool for

00:17:05.040 --> 00:17:06.040
working with JSON.

00:17:06.040 --> 00:17:11.319
There is an R package called JSON Lite, which is a very simple package.

00:17:11.319 --> 00:17:15.119
I mean, it's only a handful of functions, but it's for working with JSON data in R.

00:17:15.119 --> 00:17:18.160
The two primary functions are toJSON and fromJSON.

00:17:18.160 --> 00:17:22.880
toJSON takes an RObject, it could be a list or a data frame, and turns it into JSON.

00:17:22.880 --> 00:17:28.640
FromJSON takes JSON, saved as a character string, and turns it into an R list.

00:17:28.640 --> 00:17:32.680
Now I say this is a tangent, because the Hitter package is actually pretty good at

00:17:32.680 --> 00:17:35.839
isolating you from having to convert JSON.

00:17:35.839 --> 00:17:39.160
It's doing that in the background, and it's doing it with the JSON Lite package.

00:17:39.160 --> 00:17:44.439
But if you ever want to do it manually, JSON Lite would be a good place to start.

00:17:44.439 --> 00:17:46.079
Let's go back to Hitter.

00:17:46.079 --> 00:17:51.160
There's one more argument that you would use with the request function that's very helpful,

00:17:51.160 --> 00:17:53.319
and that's this verbose function.

00:17:53.319 --> 00:17:59.680
If you pass verbose as a function with parentheses behind it, so called function, into the get

00:17:59.680 --> 00:18:03.880
function, and that's an argument, then get function will do what it's going to do anyways,

00:18:03.880 --> 00:18:09.479
but it will print out the actual HTTP that it's sending as a request.

00:18:09.479 --> 00:18:11.239
It'll also print out the response it gets.

00:18:11.239 --> 00:18:13.520
I didn't paste that into the slide here.

00:18:13.520 --> 00:18:17.839
So here you don't have to take my word for it that these things are making the messages

00:18:17.839 --> 00:18:18.920
I'm showing you on the screen.

00:18:18.920 --> 00:18:19.920
This is the actual output.

00:18:19.920 --> 00:18:23.640
And here we can see that get is actually adding more headers than I've been including in my

00:18:23.640 --> 00:18:27.760
samples, and this is sort of what you could consider boilerplate for HTTP.

00:18:27.760 --> 00:18:31.400
It's doing it for you.

00:18:31.400 --> 00:18:38.319
So now you know how to create a response to send out to a server through a URL, or a request,

00:18:38.319 --> 00:18:39.599
I should say.

00:18:39.599 --> 00:18:43.199
Let's look at what you will get back.

00:18:43.199 --> 00:18:46.800
When you send your request, the server will process it, and it will send back a response,

00:18:46.800 --> 00:18:48.359
which is also a text file.

00:18:48.359 --> 00:18:52.839
It also has three parts, the same three parts, and the first line of it is also probably

00:18:52.839 --> 00:18:54.400
the most important line.

00:18:54.400 --> 00:18:56.680
So here's a sample response.

00:18:56.680 --> 00:19:01.239
Here I am dividing it up into the first line, the headers, and the body.

00:19:01.239 --> 00:19:04.000
If you look at the first line, the parts are kind of reversed.

00:19:04.000 --> 00:19:07.680
The first part here is the HTTP version, which, again, we don't really have to pay attention

00:19:07.680 --> 00:19:09.640
to today.

00:19:09.640 --> 00:19:16.040
The second part is a status code, which tells you whether your request succeeded or not.

00:19:16.040 --> 00:19:21.520
There are a variety of different status codes, but here 200 means that the request did succeed.

00:19:21.520 --> 00:19:25.079
This is a status code you always hope to see, it means success.

00:19:25.079 --> 00:19:29.180
And then the last part is sort of an English explanation of that status code.

00:19:29.180 --> 00:19:33.239
So every status code is a number, a three-digit number, and the English explanation helps

00:19:33.239 --> 00:19:37.400
to understand what that number means.

00:19:37.400 --> 00:19:40.199
You've probably seen status codes before just in daily surfing the web.

00:19:40.199 --> 00:19:43.400
Oftentimes, a status code will be put into the webpage you're seeing so you can understand

00:19:43.400 --> 00:19:44.439
what goes on.

00:19:44.439 --> 00:19:49.880
So for example, if you go to a place in RStudio.com that doesn't exist, you will get a 404 status

00:19:49.880 --> 00:19:54.839
code, or your web browser will receive that back from the server, and 404 means could

00:19:54.839 --> 00:19:56.479
not be found.

00:19:56.479 --> 00:20:00.000
And so here, the design of the RStudio website puts that 404 up there and says, oops, this

00:20:00.000 --> 00:20:01.199
page cannot be found.

00:20:01.199 --> 00:20:06.400
So if you've seen this before or other errors like 400, 500, that's just your web browser

00:20:06.400 --> 00:20:10.839
using the status code it got back from the server to try to explain why what you expected

00:20:10.839 --> 00:20:15.000
to happen didn't happen.

00:20:15.000 --> 00:20:17.839
There are a whole bunch of status codes.

00:20:17.839 --> 00:20:18.839
There's so many things that could go wrong.

00:20:18.839 --> 00:20:23.119
There's so many things that someone might want to talk or say through their API, and

00:20:23.119 --> 00:20:27.640
if you want to look up any particular status code, there's a very cute way to do so at

00:20:27.640 --> 00:20:28.640
http.cat.

00:20:28.640 --> 00:20:31.119
It's a little confusing.

00:20:31.119 --> 00:20:33.839
That HTTP is the start of the web address.

00:20:33.839 --> 00:20:37.839
It's not the beginning of the URL, so you'll have to write HTTP twice.

00:20:37.839 --> 00:20:45.079
But it lists all of the status codes in a cute, memorable way.

00:20:45.079 --> 00:20:48.439
So let's look at the initial request we made with Git.

00:20:48.439 --> 00:20:49.760
I saved it as R.

00:20:49.760 --> 00:20:55.959
If you want to see what we got back when Git saves its response into R, you just type R,

00:20:55.959 --> 00:20:57.680
and this is what R will show you.

00:20:57.680 --> 00:20:59.800
I've truncated a little bit at the end.

00:20:59.800 --> 00:21:03.760
It shows us that this is a response, it's a response from this URL.

00:21:03.760 --> 00:21:09.119
We got it at this date and this time, the status was 200, the content type sent back

00:21:09.119 --> 00:21:13.640
was JSON, the size was this size, and we actually see the body down here.

00:21:13.640 --> 00:21:15.520
This is some JSON that was sent back.

00:21:15.520 --> 00:21:19.920
So we were asking for something, and what we got back was this JSON.

00:21:19.920 --> 00:21:23.000
This isn't a direct HTTP message.

00:21:23.000 --> 00:21:27.260
It's an HTTP message that has been parsed into an R object, because we're now working

00:21:27.260 --> 00:21:30.520
in R, and in the background, Hitter's doing some work for us.

00:21:30.800 --> 00:21:36.000
In fact, you could think of this object that's been saved to R as like a model object in R.

00:21:36.000 --> 00:21:40.520
When you create a model, you get all sorts of information inside an object, and R doesn't

00:21:40.520 --> 00:21:44.119
necessarily know which part of that you want to see at any given time, so it just sort

00:21:44.119 --> 00:21:48.520
of saves it there, and it gives a slim display when you look at the object, but if you want

00:21:48.520 --> 00:21:51.199
the rest of the information, you'd use a helper function.

00:21:51.199 --> 00:21:56.199
Hitter comes with helper functions that allow you to access information that's in this response object.

00:21:57.199 --> 00:22:02.680
One of the first helper functions, or one of the first pieces of information that you'll

00:22:02.680 --> 00:22:04.239
want to get is the status code.

00:22:04.239 --> 00:22:08.000
This is what lets you know, or let your program know, whether it worked.

00:22:08.000 --> 00:22:12.079
You can access the number in the status code very simply with $status underscore code.

00:22:12.079 --> 00:22:13.079
So here, the R worked.

00:22:13.079 --> 00:22:14.079
We got our 200.

00:22:14.079 --> 00:22:15.079
That means it worked.

00:22:15.079 --> 00:22:21.319
Or you could get a more verbose, easy, or human understandable status message using

00:22:21.319 --> 00:22:24.640
the helper function HTTP underscore status.

00:22:24.640 --> 00:22:29.319
It prints out this list that has, you know, different components, but here we see the

00:22:29.319 --> 00:22:30.319
final one.

00:22:30.319 --> 00:22:31.319
This was successful.

00:22:31.319 --> 00:22:34.640
We got the 200 status code, and the English equivalent of 200 is okay.

00:22:37.439 --> 00:22:41.880
Now, when you're working with APIs, the status code really does matter.

00:22:41.880 --> 00:22:47.119
If you're not looking with your own eyes at the message to see if it worked or not, you

00:22:47.119 --> 00:22:52.160
will want to program defensively and have your program check to see whether the status

00:22:52.160 --> 00:22:53.800
worked or not.

00:22:53.959 --> 00:22:58.920
So it can then, you know, raise an error or a warning, and HCR has two functions that

00:22:58.920 --> 00:23:00.439
can help you do that.

00:23:00.439 --> 00:23:06.560
Warn for status will check the object to see if, you know, the status code was not 200,

00:23:06.560 --> 00:23:10.319
and if so, it will raise a warning to say, you know, this was the message, and then stop

00:23:10.319 --> 00:23:15.400
for status does almost equal, but actually stops with an error.

00:23:15.400 --> 00:23:19.079
The other thing that, if you're in the defensive mindset, you should keep in mind is there's

00:23:19.079 --> 00:23:23.000
no guarantee that these status codes are actually the correct code that comes back.

00:23:23.000 --> 00:23:27.239
You're kind of working here with someone who developed, you know, their server program

00:23:27.239 --> 00:23:30.719
on their side, and you're kind of relying on their good work, and sometimes that work

00:23:30.719 --> 00:23:32.800
might be a little bit sloppy.

00:23:32.800 --> 00:23:37.599
So if your program really depends on a certain type of data coming back or something, don't

00:23:37.599 --> 00:23:41.920
just rely on the status code to tell you that that happened, you might also actually look

00:23:41.920 --> 00:23:47.880
at the data and make sure it's that type before you let your program go on.

00:23:47.880 --> 00:23:51.359
After the status code, which is basically the only form of information, the initial

00:23:51.359 --> 00:23:55.880
line of response, you might want to access the headers, which contain metadata from

00:23:55.880 --> 00:23:59.079
the response, and you could do that with the headers helper function.

00:23:59.079 --> 00:24:01.800
It basically returns a named list of all the headers.

00:24:01.800 --> 00:24:07.280
The key values are the names, and the values are the elements in this list, and then you

00:24:07.280 --> 00:24:11.599
could access any particular one using the dollar sign syntax that you would with a list.

00:24:11.599 --> 00:24:21.199
So here I'm accessing the server header, and its value was NGINX.

00:24:21.199 --> 00:24:25.199
Within the content, if you are collecting data, this is where the data will be.

00:24:25.199 --> 00:24:28.760
It will be in the content, which is also the body of your message.

00:24:28.760 --> 00:24:32.520
You could access the content using the list syntax with dollar sign content, and what

00:24:32.520 --> 00:24:33.599
you'll get is this.

00:24:33.599 --> 00:24:38.880
This is, you know, the raw bytes that were sent back through your HTTP message.

00:24:38.880 --> 00:24:43.400
As an R user, that's probably not what you want to work with at the end of the day.

00:24:43.400 --> 00:24:47.280
So there's a helper function that can help you extract and then parse those raw bytes

00:24:47.280 --> 00:24:50.079
back into data you can access easily.

00:24:50.479 --> 00:24:56.439
And that helper function is content, so I'm using content on the R object, and then you

00:24:56.439 --> 00:25:00.239
can specify the content, what format you want that content back in.

00:25:00.239 --> 00:25:04.119
If you want those raw bytes, you can use raw, and you get the same raw bytes as using the

00:25:04.119 --> 00:25:05.119
dollar sign.

00:25:05.119 --> 00:25:14.599
But if you prefer the content as text, you can use text, and then a header will parse

00:25:14.599 --> 00:25:17.719
that raw data into text for you.

00:25:17.719 --> 00:25:24.000
This is what we get here, and then you could also just ask header to parse it, and parse

00:25:24.000 --> 00:25:29.760
will look at the header that describes the content that's in the body.

00:25:29.760 --> 00:25:33.479
It will recognize that content if it's one of these familiar contents over here, which

00:25:33.479 --> 00:25:39.079
are some of the most popular, and then it will convert the raw bytes into that content

00:25:39.079 --> 00:25:41.359
into an R list for you to use.

00:25:41.359 --> 00:25:49.680
So here's the content of R parsed.

00:25:49.680 --> 00:25:53.760
This content was JSON, and we get it back as a named list, and then you can use your

00:25:53.760 --> 00:25:58.719
R mechanics for working with lists to access the different parts of the content.

00:25:58.719 --> 00:26:03.160
This content here, by the way, just built a webpage, so this is basically a JSON format

00:26:03.160 --> 00:26:04.160
for a webpage.

00:26:04.160 --> 00:26:08.719
And I've truncated the contents here, because there's quite a bit of it.

00:26:08.719 --> 00:26:12.839
So that is all the basics of using header.

00:26:12.839 --> 00:26:18.839
It might have seemed really simple, but really all you are doing is making requests to a

00:26:18.839 --> 00:26:21.959
server, and then collecting responses from the server.

00:26:21.959 --> 00:26:28.160
The magic happens with what you do with those requests and those responses.

00:26:28.160 --> 00:26:32.479
Here I focus on getting information back from the server, because normally I think the use

00:26:32.479 --> 00:26:36.719
case for us will be there's data on the server to that particular URL, and we just want to

00:26:36.719 --> 00:26:40.839
get it so we can access it, manipulate it.

00:26:40.839 --> 00:26:46.040
However, you could use this technology to manage a webpage from R, and you could post

00:26:46.040 --> 00:26:50.160
new pages with post, you could update pages with put, and you could delete pages with

00:26:50.160 --> 00:26:51.160
delete.

