more information than I plan to go into today, but if you want data on hundreds of movies

00:31:43.800 --> 00:31:47.760
at once by Steven Spitz, Steven, this would be a case where you have to assemble the get

00:31:47.760 --> 00:31:52.839
function components into a for loop, or what I would suggest is a map function from the

00:31:52.839 --> 00:31:56.800
per package, which is a little more efficient, but you have to write a program or a script

00:31:56.800 --> 00:32:01.839
that will tell R to send a request for every movie, and then tell R what to do with response

00:32:01.839 --> 00:32:04.400
that gets back for every movie.

00:32:04.400 --> 00:32:12.800
That shouldn't take too much time, and it's completely possible to do.

00:32:12.800 --> 00:32:17.000
And then Peter's question is similar, how to instruct R to get the full list of movies.

00:32:17.000 --> 00:32:20.800
Again, you would have to know what the exhaustive list was.

00:32:20.800 --> 00:32:25.160
If you had that list of movies, then it'd be very easy to iterate over those movies,

00:32:25.160 --> 00:32:32.160
or if you had some sense of how OMDB structures its URLs, so you could programmatically change

00:32:32.160 --> 00:32:35.160
the components until you're satisfied you've gone through them all, then you could do that

00:32:35.160 --> 00:32:36.160
too.

00:32:36.160 --> 00:32:41.520
OMDB, I haven't worked with it too much, because I haven't done anything with movie database

00:32:41.520 --> 00:32:46.599
data that I'd want to spend time on, but they might actually, giving the care that they've

00:32:46.599 --> 00:32:52.239
taken to create their database, make it easy to access the entire list.

00:32:52.239 --> 00:32:54.800
We use this for a website like Yelp.

00:32:55.439 --> 00:33:03.359
Let's go determine whether or not you could use this technology for a website.

00:33:03.359 --> 00:33:06.520
What determines whether or not you could use this technology for a website will depend

00:33:06.520 --> 00:33:11.000
on whether the website contains an API for accessing the data.

00:33:11.000 --> 00:33:13.520
Not every website does, but many websites do.

00:33:13.520 --> 00:33:18.479
I don't know if Yelp has an API, but if I wanted to find out, I would start by Googling

00:33:18.479 --> 00:33:21.800
it, and it looks like it does.

00:33:21.800 --> 00:33:26.640
So yes, you could use this, and then if I was going to do that, I'd read the documentation

00:33:26.640 --> 00:33:29.319
for the API for Yelp.

00:33:29.319 --> 00:33:35.680
Web APIs that you find will be based on HTTP, the GET, the POST, those verbs, but they might

00:33:35.680 --> 00:33:39.599
have deeper features that you could take advantage of that their documentation will tell you

00:33:39.599 --> 00:33:40.599
how to do.

00:33:40.599 --> 00:33:45.640
And normally those features you take advantage of by adding things to the URL that you pass

00:33:45.640 --> 00:33:49.439
to your request.

00:33:49.439 --> 00:33:52.560
How do you learn what parameters a web API will accept by serving?

00:33:52.560 --> 00:33:55.439
Well, this is a good case for Yelp.

00:33:55.439 --> 00:33:59.680
When someone creates an API for someone else to use, if they add any features to it, they

00:33:59.680 --> 00:34:01.280
need to document it themselves.

00:34:01.280 --> 00:34:05.920
The creator of the API, so the Yelp developers here, they have complete control of what they

00:34:05.920 --> 00:34:11.199
want to put into the API, what they want to make available, and there's no real standard

00:34:11.199 --> 00:34:15.159
other than using HTTP that they'll feel obliged to stick to.

00:34:15.159 --> 00:34:17.320
So there's no universal rule.

00:34:17.320 --> 00:34:24.199
You have to learn about the API you're trying to access.

00:34:24.199 --> 00:34:25.439
Next slide, question.

00:34:25.439 --> 00:34:29.760
What package could we use to take the GET input and convert it into a data frame?

00:34:29.760 --> 00:34:39.600
We were talking about the GET input itself.

00:34:39.600 --> 00:34:43.000
That's just function arguments, but I suspect, Jordan, that you're talking about the response

00:34:43.000 --> 00:34:45.360
that you get back from GET.

00:34:45.360 --> 00:34:48.639
And the package that I would use to do that is most likely JSON-lite.

00:34:48.639 --> 00:34:55.159
It depends on if the content of that body actually comes back as JSON, but that would

00:34:55.159 --> 00:34:57.919
be the most common way for the data to come back.

00:34:57.919 --> 00:35:02.719
And then with the JSON-lite package, you could use fromJSON to turn that right into a list,

00:35:02.719 --> 00:35:06.959
which you can then make a data frame with as.data.frame.

00:35:06.959 --> 00:35:12.439
If the content comes back as something different, it's either going to be text, which you'll

00:35:12.439 --> 00:35:14.239
just have to use text manipulation tools.

00:35:14.320 --> 00:35:15.320
There probably is a package.

00:35:15.320 --> 00:35:20.959
I haven't worked with that, but if it's not JSON or text, it'll be XML, and then you can

00:35:20.959 --> 00:35:25.919
use the XML package, or even better, the XML2 package, which serves the same role as JSON-lite

00:35:25.919 --> 00:35:27.080
does for JSON.

00:35:27.080 --> 00:35:32.320
It makes it easy to work with XML data in R by changing the XML data format into R data

00:35:32.320 --> 00:35:34.320
formats, like lists and data frames.

00:35:34.320 --> 00:35:39.000
Do you ever need a special code to access an API, Steven Spitz?

00:35:39.000 --> 00:35:41.479
Yes, you almost certainly do.

00:35:41.479 --> 00:35:48.040
And then Sahil's question after this is similar.

00:35:48.040 --> 00:35:53.000
Can you use OAuth 2.0 authentication with the HTTR package request?

00:35:53.000 --> 00:35:56.879
So yes, a lot of APIs do actually want to protect their data, or at least know who you

00:35:56.879 --> 00:36:01.679
are if you're coming to use the data, so they require some sort of authentication.

00:36:01.679 --> 00:36:08.040
You can use authentication with HTTR package.

00:36:08.040 --> 00:36:15.600
Here we're going beyond my abilities as a statistician to do things, but if you want

00:36:15.600 --> 00:36:19.760
to set HTTP authentication, I'm in the help page for Git.

00:36:19.760 --> 00:36:25.159
It has a link right here to authenticate, which is the helper function in HTTR that

00:36:25.159 --> 00:36:28.879
will help you do that, and then there's some examples down here about how you could go

00:36:28.879 --> 00:36:29.879
about that.

00:36:29.879 --> 00:36:34.919
So if you wanted to send a Git request to, for example, HTTP bin, which we were using

00:36:34.919 --> 00:36:37.239
earlier, you could send it right to that URL.

00:36:37.239 --> 00:36:40.719
But if you need to authenticate with the user and the password, you would add authenticate

00:36:40.719 --> 00:36:46.320
to the request, and it would add your user and password to the HTTP message that it sends.

00:36:46.320 --> 00:36:52.199
The same way like adding add headers adds headers to your message.

00:36:52.199 --> 00:36:58.520
I don't have any examples to show you about that, so I apologize, guys.

00:36:58.520 --> 00:37:05.800
If my job is a firewall, how do I ask IT to let me through so I can get data?

00:37:05.800 --> 00:37:08.360
If you have a firewall, that's obviously a difficulty.

00:37:08.360 --> 00:37:09.679
This is a place where I'm going to have to punt.

00:37:09.679 --> 00:37:15.919
I myself would have to ask IT, and I would be very dependent on what they tell me back.

00:37:15.919 --> 00:37:25.479
So the only thing I can tell you is that you should ask IT, and they, doing what IT does

00:37:25.479 --> 00:37:28.399
on a day-to-day basis, should be familiar with how to give you permission to go through

00:37:28.399 --> 00:37:29.399
a firewall.

00:37:29.399 --> 00:37:35.199
How do you make sure you don't overload the web server with requests?

00:37:35.199 --> 00:37:40.239
Well, if you are automating your work with a map function or a for loop, there will be

00:37:40.239 --> 00:37:45.360
a lot of requests, and depending on what sort of defensive measures that website has to

00:37:45.360 --> 00:37:51.800
prevent bots or whatnot, you might have to have the system sleep between each iteration

00:37:51.800 --> 00:37:54.280
so they don't happen one after another or whatnot.

00:37:54.840 --> 00:38:00.080
If you're working with a web API, they are likely expecting lots of requests.

00:38:00.080 --> 00:38:03.000
This is a way to transfer data.

00:38:03.000 --> 00:38:07.760
So if you're working with something like OMDB, which is purposely sending data across, you

00:38:07.760 --> 00:38:11.000
might not run into the overload that you expect.

00:38:11.000 --> 00:38:15.040
If you're working with a basic website, which just thinks users are visiting it, and the

00:38:15.040 --> 00:38:19.600
API you're relying on is the web browser API to build that website, well, if you hit that

00:38:19.800 --> 00:38:26.239
frequently, yeah, you might trigger some requests, some security that says, like, you know, too

00:38:26.239 --> 00:38:28.800
many requests in a certain time frame.

00:38:28.800 --> 00:38:34.239
I think, you know, this is some sort of cyber attack, and I think the best way to deal with

00:38:34.239 --> 00:38:35.679
that would be to just not sleep.

00:38:39.000 --> 00:38:39.520
Okay.

00:38:40.159 --> 00:38:41.959
John has a very insightful question.

00:38:41.959 --> 00:38:43.959
How can you contrast Hitter with RVest?

00:38:43.959 --> 00:38:48.840
So RVest is a package that's designed to help you scrape data off the web, and RVest will

00:38:48.840 --> 00:38:51.080
be the topic of the November 30th workshop.

00:38:51.080 --> 00:38:53.879
Now, RVest is really where I have more experience.

00:38:53.879 --> 00:38:59.080
Like I said a few times, or it's come out a few times, I don't work with web APIs that

00:38:59.080 --> 00:39:01.320
often, but I do scrape data off the web.

00:39:01.320 --> 00:39:05.280
For me, I'm mostly interested in just, like, idiosyncratic data that probably isn't shared

00:39:05.280 --> 00:39:08.120
over an API, but it is on a web page.

00:39:08.120 --> 00:39:18.120
So an example of this would be if we didn't go to OMDB, but we went to IMDB, which is

00:39:18.120 --> 00:39:23.800
the Internet Movie Database, you know, there's all sorts of data here.

00:39:23.800 --> 00:39:26.360
Let's just pick a movie, the Lego Batman movie.

00:39:26.360 --> 00:39:28.360
I hope I didn't just mention it.

00:39:28.360 --> 00:39:30.360
I think I might.

00:39:30.360 --> 00:39:32.360
No, let's stop that.

00:39:34.360 --> 00:39:36.360
Almost Christmas.

00:39:38.919 --> 00:39:42.840
Down here, you know, there's a table of actors and actresses and what roles they play.

00:39:42.840 --> 00:39:46.120
There's comments, metadata, trivia.

00:39:46.120 --> 00:39:49.000
All these things are data that's in this web page.

00:39:49.000 --> 00:39:55.719
If we wanted to look at the source of the web page, you know, we will see a lot of HTML,

00:39:55.719 --> 00:39:59.959
but in that HTML, there's the data that we're looking at.

00:39:59.959 --> 00:40:05.080
It hasn't been put in a place that's easy for us to access, so if we wanted it, we'd

00:40:05.080 --> 00:40:09.320
basically have to take down this HTML and do character processing, string processing

00:40:09.320 --> 00:40:12.120
on it to get the data we want back from it.

00:40:12.120 --> 00:40:15.560
That's what I'm calling web scraping, and that's what the RVest package is designed

00:40:15.560 --> 00:40:16.760
to do.

00:40:16.760 --> 00:40:22.280
It's a down and dirty way to just go in there and take what you want and probably cause

00:40:22.280 --> 00:40:27.239
legal trouble if you try to sell it or something, but it gives you full freedom to get anything

00:40:27.239 --> 00:40:30.520
you see on the internet, and that's what we'll talk about next time.

00:40:30.520 --> 00:40:33.320
HTTR is a much more mannerly package.

00:40:33.320 --> 00:40:37.800
It's for data that the people who put it on the internet expected others to come get,

00:40:37.800 --> 00:40:41.719
and they've organized it in a nice, neat way, and they've arranged so when you send

00:40:41.719 --> 00:40:47.719
them get requests, you can get back a response with the data in it.

00:40:47.719 --> 00:40:53.159
So if you're contemplating web scraping, and I'll say this on November 30th too, the

00:40:53.159 --> 00:40:55.159
first thing you should always do is check to see if the data's available through some

00:40:55.159 --> 00:40:59.560
sort of API, because it would save you a lot of time if you could use HTTR.

00:40:59.560 --> 00:41:00.679
You will save a lot of time.

00:41:00.679 --> 00:41:05.000
RVest is a messy data that you really have to clean up.

00:41:05.000 --> 00:41:10.040
So the difference between HTTR and RVest is the difference between APIs and web scraping.

00:41:10.120 --> 00:41:11.719
This is a convenient place to stop.

00:41:11.719 --> 00:41:15.639
I apologize if I haven't answered some of your questions.

00:41:15.639 --> 00:41:21.159
My take-home message to you is that this technology is fairly simple at the level we're using

00:41:21.159 --> 00:41:23.959
it, and you can just build on it from there.

00:41:23.959 --> 00:41:28.439
If you want to go further, start with the vignettes for HTTR.

